Active Power Analysis and Prediction using LSTM¶

- Name : Vikram Pande¶
- Unity ID: vspande¶

INTRODUCTION¶

Households use energies for different purposes. It is a very common thing and needs to be analysed on daily to yearly basis to get the insights of average energy consumption of a particular household and combined consumptions of many. The total energy consumed by a household other than sub meter appliances is Global Active Power. The power which bounces back and forth without any usage or leakage is Global Reactive Power. There is power calculated from the unit meteres ( commonly 3 because of three phase ). It is important to know how much energy the appliances actually require. This project is aiming to predict the overall active power consumption of household.

Problem Statement¶

This project is mainly focusing on predicition and comparison the Active Energy usage of a particular Household for various time instances such as monthly, weekly, daily and hourly. The plan is to compare active power changes over different time instances, compare and estimate the model performance.

This task will be a Time-Series Analysis type of task. There are multiple state-of-art TimeSeries models are available such as ARIMA, SARIMA, Single Exponential etc. The stat-of-art Deep Learning RNN based LSTM model is also pretty common while solving Time Series because of accurate results.

Dataset¶

The dataset "Individual household electric power consumption Data Set" used for the analysis and prediction purpose is from UCI Machine Learning repo which can be found here.

The dataset desribes the power consumption of a particular house in France in the period of December 2006 to November 2010, overall 4 years. The reason to chose this dataset is that it has 2075259 instances of data measured in 4 years with timestamp which is perfect to learn Time Series Problems as beginner.

The dataset mainly talks about global active power, global reactive power , intensity, voltage and readings from three submeters. The Active Power is the power consumed by equipment directly ignoring values from sub-meters. From the above parameters, we can calculate Active Power by the formula:

Active Power = (Global Active Power) (1000/60) - (summation of submeters) Active Power = (global_active_power 1000/60 - sub_metering_1 - sub_metering_2 - sub_metering_3) formula

Methodology¶

The project aims to predict the values of active power with the help of given timestamps. The project is mainly divided into three parts such as data preparation, visualisations and model building.

Data Preparation¶

  • For data preparation, the whole dataset is divided into subsets of data grouped by the average values of hour, days, weeks, months and years. Data preprocessing is done by manipulating null values and some columns.

Data Visualization¶

  • The trends of Active Power are visualised based on different time instances before training.
  • The trends of Active power are visualised after training the model and compared before-after results by overlaying graph plot structure.
  • Loss of the model is visualised which should be decreasing over the epochs.

Modeling¶

Why LSTM?¶
  • This is the main part of the project where comparison over time instances is done. There are many techniques to tackle Time Series problems such as AR, VAR, ARIMA, SARIMA, SES etc. However, for this task a powerful deep learning model LSTM ( Long-Short-Term-Memory ) is used because it is a sequential model which helps in predicting future data with better accuracy and decision making. LSTM is capable to capture underlying patterns for both long term as well as short term time instances. It is capable of taking input of different lengths which is better for Time Series. These are some main reasons to use LSTM architecture.
  • There are type of LSTM such as Single/Uni Variate LSTM, BiVariate LSTM and multivariate LSTM. For this project Single/Univariate LSTM is used.
A little bit about LSTM:¶
  • LSTM is a Recurrent Neural Network which is able to remember values over arbitrary instances. LSTM has feedback connections. The LSTM architecture aims to provide a short-term memory for RNN that can last thousands of timesteps, thus long short-term memory. A common LSTM unit is composed of a cell, an input gate, an output gate and a forget gate. The cell remembers values over arbitrary time intervals and the three gates regulate the flow of information into and out of the cell. LSTM deals with Vanishing Gradient Problem. Hence, LSTM is well suited for continuous data problems like Time Series. source: Wikipedia

For this Project:¶
  • For this particular task, single variate LSTM is used. It is designed in such a way that it takes sliding window (look back in the code below) of 30 datasamples and predicts 31st, again increasing count of sliding window by 1. So, supppose, active power on each day for the first 30 days of month of January is taken as a sliding window (look back) then it will predict the output power on 31st January. Then, again by increasing count by 1, it will take 30 data samples from January 2nd to January 31st and will predict active power on February 1st and so on. This kind of structure helps improve accuracy of precitions.
  • As this is a Time Series type of task, loss function MSE ( Mean Squared Error) is used because time series is nothing but a type of Regression problem. MSE shows the difference between predicted and actual values which is useful to indicate how the predictions differ from original.
  • Most of the times, time series related data is sparse in nature. ADAM is the best optimizer to deal with this kind of nature. Hence, ADAM is used with typical learning rate as 0.01.
  • For the training purpose, 80 % of data is taken as training data and remaining 20 % as test data.
  • As PyTorch models require input in tensors, numpy arrays of data are converted into tensors.
  • Both MAPE and RMSE are used as evaluation metric.
  • Seed is kept as 1 to get same results.

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

Testing the hypothesis that the mean of Daily Active Power Hourly is 9 at the significance level 5%.

  • Assume, H0: Mean is 9
  • H1: otherwise.
In [19]:
# Filtering Daily Data
consumption_data['day'] = consumption_data.index.day
In [20]:
hourly_activepower_mean = consumption_data.groupby(['day'])['active_power'].mean().reset_index()
# hourly_activepower_mean
In [21]:
res = stats.ttest_1samp(hourly_activepower_mean, 9)
res

        print('Fail to reject H0')
    else:
        print('Reject H0')

6. Predicitons and Model Building: LSTM¶

In [28]:
#Lists to store metrics
mape_list = []
rmse_list = []
In [29]:
# Build LSTM model
input_dim = 1
hidden_dim = 32
num_layers = 2
output_dim = 1

# Model as a class
class LSTM(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_dim, num_layers, output_dim):
        super(LSTM, self).__init__()
        
        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim # Hidden dimensions

        self.num_layers = num_layers # Number of hidden layers

        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(input_dim, hidden_dim, num_layers, batch_first=True) #batch_first=True -> input/output tensors in shape

        self.fc = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, output_dim)  # Readout layer

    def forward(self, x):
        h0 = torch.zeros(self.num_layers, x.size(0), self.hidden_dim).requires_grad_() #hidden state with zeros

        c0 = torch.zeros(self.num_layers, x.size(0), self.hidden_dim).requires_grad_() # Initialize cell state

        out, (hn, cn) = self.lstm(x, (h0.detach(), c0.detach())) # Detatch due to backpropagation

        out = self.fc(out[:, -1, :])  # Index hidden state of last time step

        return out
    
# input parameters to model    
model = LSTM(input_dim=input_dim, hidden_dim=hidden_dim, output_dim=output_dim, num_layers=num_layers)

#Define loss function
loss_fn = torch.nn.MSELoss() # Mean Squared Error Loss function as Time-Series Problem

#Define optimiser
optimiser = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.01) # Adam Optimiser

# Describe Model 
print(model)
print(len(list(model.parameters())))
for i in range(len(list(model.parameters()))):
    print(list(model.parameters())[i].size())

LSTM(
  (lstm): LSTM(1, 32, num_layers=2, batch_first=True)
  (fc): Linear(in_features=32, out_features=1, bias=True)
)

# Data Preparation Function
training_data_len = math.ceil(len(valuesM)* 0.80) # training data 80%
def load_data(scaled, look_back):
    data_raw = scaled # convert to numpy array
    data = []
    # create all possible sequences of length look_back
    for index in range(len(data_raw) - look_back): 
        data.append(data_raw[index: index + look_back])
    
    data = np.array(data);
    test_set_size = int(np.round(0.2*data.shape[0]));
    train_set_size = data.shape[0] - (test_set_size);
    
    x_train = data[:train_set_size,:-1,:]
    y_train = data[:train_set_size,-1,:]
    
    x_test = data[train_set_size:,:-1]
    y_test = data[train_set_size:,-1,:]
    
    return [x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test]

rmse_list.append(testScoreH)
mape_list.append(testMapeH)

8. Conclusion and Future Scope¶

Conclusion:¶

  • From the above table of result metrics, it can be said that the most efficient time instance to predict the values is Monthly instance as we got less MAPE of 13% and RMSE as compared to other time instances. Even if 1.25% of data was missing, model was able to perform well. If the values were not missing, model performance would have been more better than the current.
  • The best time instances after monthly instance are weekly and daily. For daily instance, results are pretty good as we got MAPE 18%. This means if the model were able to forecast in future, it will only forecast 18 values incorrectly, giving 82 correct values which is acceptable.
  • It is observed that for the tightly coupled data such as for hourly instance, model takes time for computation and hence for 70 epochs, MAPE was around 37 %. If epochs are increased till appropriate amount, there is a chance to get a lower value of MAPE.

Future Scope:¶

  • For this task, only single variate LSTM was used taking only timestamp/ timeseries as input and predicting the output/ target variable. For the same task, multivariate LSTM could be used to forecast the target variable taking more than one input features.
  • If the high computational devices are available, model could be trained at instance of seconds and with the help of proper hyperparameter tuning, most accurate results could be obtained.
